increased contact between culturally distinct groups in some cases gives rise to more intense conflict. Yet individuals who get to know each other better generally like each other better. Can these apparently conflicting generalizations both be true? asks Forbes. They are, he argues, and he takes contemporary social science to task for failing to show how and why this is possible. The author clarifies the weaknesses of contact theory, develops an alternative "linguistic model" of ethnic conflict, and concludes with penetrating reflections on the politics and methodology of the social sciences today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCritical theory. 0aCulture conflict. 0aEthnic conflict. 0aEthnocentrism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Reference.2bisacsh1 aCurnen, Mary G. McCrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSpiro, Howard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSt James, Deborah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300146417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300146417.jpg  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles